LessonsLearned:
&lt;b&gt;&lt;/b&gt;Lessons learned:&lt;br&gt;All process hazards, including all possible dangerous interactions between chemicals, should be identified. 
Risk studies on batch processes should consider all process steps and conditions. Measures eliminating the existence of an explosive atmosphere should always have priority to measures preventing the ignition of that atmosphere.  
Loading of products through an open manhole into flammable atmosphere is not good practice.
Recommendations of risk studies and incident investigations need to be followed up systematically.
The safety responsibilities and duties of management should be clearly identified.
Work instructions should be clear and periodically reviewed and actualised. The process control system should correspond to the intended process method. 
All changes to the process and process working methods should be evaluated as to their impact on safety (management of change procedure). The management of change procedure should also address changes in organisational structure or in staff.&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;Actions taken/imposed:&lt;br&gt;
The lean air project was implemented before restartup of the production
lines. Other processes involving opening of manholes where identified
and were only accepted to start up again if no flammable substances
were involved. &lt;br&gt;
Raw materials are added via closed systems. Buckets are replaced by closed recipients. &lt;br&gt;
All process risk studies will be revised and completed within a short
time period. Priorities for the risk analysis program were made based
on hazard potential of the processes involved. &lt;br&gt;
The adaption process of the safety management system to the guidelines
of the new group is accelerated and expected to be complete before the
end of 2006, correcting at the same time the shortcomings identified in
the accident investigation. &lt;br&gt;
Management will be instructed on safety responsibilities and duties. &lt;b&gt;&lt;br&gt;
&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;
